"""
MKT Context Commentary — Proverbs chapters 22–24
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-proverbs-22-24.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/proverbs.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/proverbs.json

Key decisions:
- Prov 22:17-24:22 closely parallels the Egyptian Instruction of Amenemope
  (c.1200 BCE, 30 chapters); the "thirty sayings" of 22:20 refers to this.
  This is the most documented ANE borrowing in Proverbs.
- The city gate (sha'ar) as legal/commercial venue: 22:22, 23:10, 24:7
- The go'el (kinsman-redeemer) institution at 23:11
- 23:29-35: the wine passage is one of the most vivid ANE addiction descriptions
- 24:16: the righteous-falls-seven-times proverb is a pattern of resilience
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

PROVERBS = {
  "22": {
    "1": "<p>The preference for a good name over wealth reflects the ANE honor-economy in which reputation was the primary social currency. In a world without credit bureaus or formal contracts, a good name (<em>shem tov</em>) was the practical foundation for commerce, patronage, and marriage alliances. 'Favor' (<em>chen</em>) — grace or goodwill in the eyes of others — is the social capital that opens doors wealth alone cannot.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The theological leveling principle — 'the LORD made them both' — counters the ANE tendency to explain social stratification as divinely ordained. Mesopotamian texts often portrayed the gods as creating humans in different classes for different purposes. Proverbs asserts a common creatureliness: both rich and poor are <em>asah</em> (made, crafted) by the same Creator, which grounds the ethical obligations that follow.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The prudent person (<em>arum</em>) sees danger and hides; the naive (<em>peti</em>) passes on and suffers. <em>Arum</em> (prudent, shrewd) is the same word used of the serpent in Gen 3:1 — not ethically negative in itself but indicating sharp practical perception. The ANE wisdom tradition prized exactly this capacity: the ability to read social situations and dangers before they became acute.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Humility' (<em>anavah</em>) and 'fear of the LORD' (<em>yirat Adonai</em>) together yield material prosperity — the standard Deuteronomic blessing formula. The pairing of the vertical virtue (fear of God) with the social virtue (humility toward humans) as the combined source of blessing is characteristic of Proverbs' integrated theology: proper orientation toward God and toward society are inseparable.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Thorns and snares (<em>tsenim pachim</em>) in the path of the perverse — the agricultural hazards of Palestinian terrain as an image of moral danger. Thorns in fields and snares for animals were familiar daily hazards; their use as metaphors for the consequences of moral deviance grounds the abstract in sensory experience.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Train a child in the way he should go' (<em>chanokh lana'ar al pi darko</em>) — <em>chanokh</em> (to train, dedicate, initiate) is the root of Hanukkah; it has the sense of inaugurating someone into proper use. 'The way he should go' is debated: it may mean 'the way appropriate to him' (his natural bent) or 'his proper way' (the moral path). Hebrew education was primarily oral — the child was trained through repeated exposure to wisdom sayings, stories, and liturgy in the home context.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'The borrower is slave to the lender' — debt in the ancient world was not merely financial but social. Debt-slavery was a real institution in the ANE: a person unable to repay could be taken as a slave or surrender family members (Neh 5:1-5; 2 Kgs 4:1). The proverb describes a social reality of the ancient economy that modern readers experience only in metaphor.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Whoever sows injustice will reap trouble' — the agricultural metaphor of moral causation. The sowing-reaping pattern (<em>zara</em> / <em>qatsar</em>) is one of the most ancient moral frameworks, expressing the slow but inevitable operation of consequence. 'The weapon of his rage will be broken' (<em>shebet evrato yichleh</em>) — the rod or weapon of domination exhausts itself; the oppressor's instrument of power has a lifespan.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'A generous person will be blessed, for he shares his bread with the poor' — the redistribution obligation is central to Israelite social ethics (Lev 19:9-10; Deut 15:11). The word 'generous' is literally 'good of eye' (<em>tov ayin</em>) — the opposite of the 'evil eye' of the miser (23:6). In ANE culture, hospitality and bread-sharing created social bonds and obligations that structured community life.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Drive out the mocker, and conflict goes with him' — the <em>lets</em> (mocker, scoffer) is a specific social type in Proverbs who is immune to correction and disrupts community. The practical observation: social conflict is often anchored in one or a few individuals whose expulsion restores order. This is sociological realism rather than idealism.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Whoever loves a pure heart and whose speech is gracious will have the king as his friend' — access to royal patronage through demonstrated virtue. In ANE court culture, advancement depended on character traits visible to patrons: purity of heart (moral reliability) and gracious speech (social competence) were the twin qualifications for royal favor.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'The eyes of the LORD watch over knowledge' — divine protection of those who possess and dispense true wisdom. In ANE royal ideology, the king's eyes were everywhere as a surveillance metaphor (cf. 'the king's eyes and ears' as intelligence officers). Proverbs attributes this watchfulness to God: knowledge and its possessors are under his protection.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'The sluggard says, There is a lion outside!' — the implausible excuse for inaction. Lions in ancient Israel were a real hazard in certain areas (1 Sam 17:34; 1 Kgs 13:24), but using them as an excuse to avoid work in the streets was the kind of obvious exaggeration that the wisdom tradition skewers. The humor is deliberate: the sluggard's excuse is technically possible but transparently absurd.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'The mouth of an adulterous woman is a deep pit' — the sexual-danger motif that runs through Prov 1-9. 'Deep pit' (<em>shuchah amukah</em>) echoes the underworld imagery used of the foreign woman throughout chapters 1-9; her mouth/words are the trap. 'Under the LORD's displeasure' — the man who falls is described as one under divine disfavor, which frames the moral failure in theological terms.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Foolishness is bound up in the heart of a child, but the rod of discipline will drive it out' — ANE child-rearing was explicitly physical. The rod (<em>shevet</em>) is the same instrument used by shepherds and by divine discipline (Ps 23:4). The metaphysics of moral formation here is organic: folly is bound into the child's natural constitution and requires active intervention, not merely education, to expel.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Two behaviors leading to the same outcome (poverty): oppressing the poor to enrich oneself, and giving gifts to the wealthy. Both are economically irrational and morally inverted. The second is a form of sycophancy or bribery — using resources to cultivate the already-powerful rather than to build genuine social capital.</p>",
    "17": "<p>22:17-21 opens the 'Words of the Wise' collection, which scholars recognize as closely parallel to the Egyptian <em>Instruction of Amenemope</em> (c.1200 BCE), a 30-chapter royal wisdom text. The parallels are so close that direct literary dependence is widely accepted. This is not plagiarism in the ancient sense but the international sharing of wisdom that characterized court culture across the ancient Near East — Egypt, Mesopotamia, and Israel shared a common wisdom tradition.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'To have them ready on your lips' — the internalization of wisdom sayings for ready use. The oral character of ancient education meant that maxims were memorized for deployment in specific situations. The wisdom of the teacher is 'pleasant' (<em>nayim</em>) when internalized — not merely informational but formative.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'I am teaching you today — you specifically' (<em>af attah</em> — 'even you' or 'you in particular') — the personalizing of wisdom instruction. The direct address throughout these chapters ('my son') and the specific 'you' creates the intimacy of the master-disciple relationship that was the primary pedagogy of the ancient world.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'Thirty excellent sayings' (<em>shloshim</em>) — the reference to 'thirty' almost certainly points to the thirty chapters of the Egyptian <em>Instruction of Amenemope</em>. The Proverbs compiler is announcing that what follows is an organized wisdom collection of comparable scope and authority to the Egyptian source. This demonstrates the cosmopolitan intellectual context of Israelite wisdom: Egypt's wisdom school is a legitimate source to be appropriated and reframed for Yahwistic purposes.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Accurate answers to those who send you' — court messenger context. The sage trained to give reliable, precise reports to those who commissioned him was valuable in royal administration. Truth-telling in a court context was not merely moral but functionally essential: inaccurate reports led to diplomatic and military failures.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Do not rob the poor because they are poor, or crush the afflicted at the city gate' — the gate (<em>sha'ar</em>) as the venue for legal oppression. The city gate was where legal proceedings, commerce, and civil administration occurred; the powerful could corrupt judicial processes there against the vulnerable. The specific prohibition implies this was a common practice.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'The LORD will take up their case' (<em>yariv et rivam</em>) — God as the legal advocate (<em>yariv</em>) of the poor whose case human courts fail to hear. The verb <em>ruv</em> (to contend, plead a case) is legal language; God enters the judicial process as the go'el (kinsman-redeemer) of those who have no human advocate.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'Do not befriend an angry man' — the social contagion principle. Emotional dispositions were understood in the ancient world to be transmitted through association; the proverb applies this to anger specifically. One's character is shaped by the company one keeps — a wisdom-tradition constant that reflects the social learning dynamics of close community life.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'Lest you learn his ways and set a trap for yourself' — the acquisition of bad habits through modeling is gradual and unconscious. The trap (<em>moqesh</em>) — a snare for animals — implies that the learner of bad habits does not see himself being caught; he thinks he is freely adopting a useful behavior while actually being ensnared.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Pledging security for loans was a dangerous practice in the ancient economy. Without limited liability, a guarantor bore full responsibility for the debt. This made casual loan guarantees a path to debt-slavery. The wisdom tradition consistently warns against this (Prov 6:1-5, 11:15, 17:18) — reflecting the economic reality that debt destroyed families.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'Why let him take away your bed from under you?' — the bed (<em>mishkav</em>) as the last possession. In ancient legal practice, a creditor could seize property; the bed or sleeping mat was the most basic household item. The Mosaic law protected the cloak given as pledge from overnight retention (Exod 22:26-27) precisely because the poor had nothing else to sleep in.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'Do not move the ancient boundary stone' (<em>gevul olam</em>) — the stone marker of property boundaries was a sacred institution protected by explicit covenant curse (Deut 19:14, 27:17). In agricultural societies, these stones established legal title to land; moving them was a form of theft affecting the entire household's economic survival. The 'ancient' (<em>olam</em>) marker reinforces that these boundaries represent the established social order.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'He will serve kings — not obscure people' — the career aspiration embedded in the wisdom tradition. Skill (<em>mahir</em>, swift/expert) at one's craft was the means of upward mobility in the ANE. Advancement to royal service was the highest goal; the proverb motivates excellence by pointing toward its ultimate social reward.</p>"
  },
  "23": {
    "1": "<p>Dining protocol at a ruler's table — court etiquette was a major concern of ANE wisdom literature. Egyptian court manuals (including Amenemope) and Mesopotamian wisdom texts contain detailed instructions for behavior before patrons and superiors. How one ate communicated social status, self-control, and reliability; poor dining manners were career-ending at the royal court.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Put a knife to your throat if you have an unruly appetite' — dramatic hyperbole for self-control at the ruler's table. The 'baal nefesh' (one with a powerful appetite/soul) should exercise radical restraint in the patron's presence. Conspicuous consumption at a ruler's table signaled greed, which undermined the trust relationships essential to court service.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'That food is deceptive' — the ruler's delicacies are a test, not a benefit. The wisdom tradition treats lavish hospitality with suspicion: the real purpose may be to assess the guest's character, create obligation, or soften someone up for a request. 'Bread of deception' is a category appearing in Prov 20:17; the wise person reads the social meaning behind the food.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Do not wear yourself out trying to get rich' — the ANE court context clarifies this: the sage advising a young man entering royal service warns against the obsessive wealth-pursuit that warps judgment. 'Have the wisdom to show restraint' (<em>min binatekha chadal</em>) — literally 'from your understanding, cease.' True wisdom includes knowing when to stop.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Riches sprout wings and fly away like an eagle into the sky' — the eagle's sudden, distant flight is a vivid image of wealth's volatility. In an agricultural economy subject to drought, war, disease, and taxation, fortunes could evaporate rapidly. The proverb counters the illusion of permanent wealth accumulation with a realistic portrait of its transience.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'The bread of a stingy man' (<em>lechem ra ayin</em>) — literally 'bread of an evil eye.' The 'evil eye' (<em>ra ayin</em>) in the ANE was not merely a metaphor but a concept in popular belief: the gaze of envy or ill-will could cause harm. Applied to the miser, it means his spirit of envy and reluctance poisons even his hospitality. Eating with him is socially and spiritually hazardous.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'He is one who keeps a running count in his mind' (<em>kemo she'ar benafsho ken hu</em>) — literally 'as he calculates in his soul, so he is.' The miser is mentally calculating the cost of every bite his guest takes even while verbally offering more. The disconnect between his words and his inner attitude is the ANE wisdom tradition's critique of false hospitality.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'You will vomit up the little you ate' — the physical result of eating with the stingy man (the social discomfort ultimately nauseates). 'Your pleasant words will have been wasted' — the social investment in the relationship yields nothing; every gracious word spoken to cultivate the miser's patronage is expended without return.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Do not speak to a fool, for he will only scorn the wisdom behind your words' — the audience qualification for wisdom teaching. In ANE court culture, the selection of suitable students was crucial; dispensing wisdom to those constitutionally incapable of receiving it was both futile and demeaning to the wisdom itself. The fool's scorn (<em>yalutz</em>) actively undermines the transmission of wisdom.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Do not move an ancient boundary stone, and do not enter the fields of orphans' — the orphan's land is specifically protected because orphans had no male guardian to defend their legal interests. This verse pairs with 22:28 (boundary stones) and intensifies the protection: the most vulnerable landowners (orphans without fathers) receive the most explicit protection.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Their Redeemer is strong; he will plead their case' — the <em>go'el</em> (kinsman-redeemer) institution. The <em>go'el</em> was the nearest male relative responsible for redeeming family members from debt-slavery, avenging their blood, and restoring their property (Lev 25:25-28; Ruth 2-4; Num 35:19). For orphans without human kin, God himself is their <em>go'el</em> — a remarkable claim that divine kinship fills the gap where human kinship has failed.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Devote your heart to instruction and your ears to words of knowledge' — the whole-person orientation that wisdom requires. Heart (<em>lev</em>) and ears (<em>oznaim</em>) together represent the integration of understanding and reception; wisdom is not merely intellectual apprehension but the reorientation of the entire person toward its reception.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Do not withhold discipline from a child; if you strike him with the rod, he will not die' — a counter to parental softness. The claim 'he will not die' addresses the fear that physical correction would harm the child; the wisdom tradition asserts that the rod's pain is temporary while its benefit is lasting. The cultural background is an ancient world in which undisciplined children were a social hazard.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'You will save his life from death' (<em>sheol</em>) — the stakes of parental discipline: it is life-or-death. An undisciplined young man in ancient society faced real mortal dangers — involvement in violence, debt, sexual license leading to blood-feuds or disease. The rod as salvation-instrument is a stark contrast to the modern therapeutic frame for discipline.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'My son, if your heart is wise, then my heart will be glad' — the emotional investment of the teacher in the student. The sage-student relationship in the ANE was quasi-parental; the teacher's honor was implicated in the student's conduct. Egyptian wisdom texts (Instructions of Ptahhotep, Amenemope) similarly express the teacher's personal stake in the student's wisdom.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'My inmost being will rejoice when your lips speak what is right' — <em>kilyotai</em> (my kidneys/inmost being) is the seat of deep emotion in Hebrew anthropology (cf. Ps 16:7, 73:21). The teacher's visceral joy at the student's right speech is the pedagogical relationship at its most intimate.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Do not let your heart envy sinners, but live in the fear of the LORD all day long' — the instruction addresses a specific temptation of young men: the apparent prosperity of those who do not follow wisdom's path. 'All day long' (<em>kol hayom</em>) — the fear of the LORD is not an occasional posture but the continuous orientation of an entire day's consciousness.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Surely there is a future, and your hope will not be cut off' (<em>acharit vetikvatkha lo tikaret</em>) — the eschatological incentive for present fidelity. <em>Acharit</em> (future, end, latter things) and <em>tiqvah</em> (hope, cord — cf. Rahab's scarlet cord) together assert that the path of wisdom leads to a genuine future outcome, not premature termination.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Keep your heart on the right path' (<em>asher laderekh libekha</em>) — path-metaphor for moral life. The direction of the heart determines the direction of the life. ANE wisdom literature consistently used the path/road metaphor for moral conduct (Egyptian <em>maat</em> was the path of cosmic order; Proverbs' <em>derekh</em> is the personal moral equivalent).</p>",
    "20": "<p>'Do not be among those who drink too much wine or gorge themselves on meat' — the symposium culture of the ANE. Heavy drinking was associated with aristocratic social gatherings (drinking parties appear in Isa 5:11-12, Amos 6:4-7); the wisdom tradition consistently warned against associating with those who defined community by excess consumption.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'The drunkard and the glutton will come to poverty' — economic ruin as the consequence of appetite-domination. Both require constant expenditure on pleasure; both impair the capacity for productive work. The proverb is economic analysis as much as moral instruction: excess consumption is a path to economic collapse.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Listen to your father who gave you life, and do not despise your mother when she grows old' — the fifth commandment embedded in wisdom instruction. The aging mother is specifically mentioned — her vulnerability when past productive years makes her a specific target of the filial obligation. The ANE context: honor of parents was a social norm backed by legal sanction in many legal codes (including Hammurabi's).</p>",
    "23": "<p>'Buy the truth and do not sell it' — wisdom as an economic metaphor. <em>Emet</em> (truth), <em>chochmah</em> (wisdom), <em>musar</em> (instruction/discipline), and <em>binah</em> (understanding) are all priced as purchasable commodities in this verse. The market metaphor for wisdom reflects the ANE reality that education required real investment; the sage's instruction was not free.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'The father of a righteous child will greatly rejoice' — the multigenerational perspective of wisdom. The father's investment in wisdom-formation is rewarded in the son's character. The joy at a wise son is both personal (pride in the child) and social (the son represents the family's reputation in the community).</p>",
    "25": "<p>'Let your father and mother be glad; let the one who bore you rejoice' — the mother's specific joy at the wise child. Hebrew <em>yoledetekha</em> (the one who bore you) is a strong reminder of physical birth — the one who labored to bring the child into existence has a deep stake in his moral formation.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'My son, give me your heart, and let your eyes keep watch over my ways' — the reciprocity of the teaching relationship. The student gives his heart (inner attention, commitment); the teacher gives his ways (observable conduct, modeled wisdom). Wisdom is transmitted not just through maxims but through watching and imitating the life of the sage.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'A prostitute is a deep pit, and an immoral woman is a narrow well' (<em>shuchah amukah...beer tsarah</em>) — the spatial imagery of entrapment. A pit (<em>shuchah</em>) can be fallen into; a narrow well (<em>beer tsarah</em>) is one from which there is no escape once inside. The architectural metaphors describe the social and moral trap of sexual license — easy to enter, nearly impossible to exit.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'She lies in wait like a hunter and multiplies the unfaithful among men' — the immoral woman as active predator. <em>Chotet</em> (hunter/ambusher) — she hunts systematically, not accidentally. The social effect is described in epidemiological terms: she 'multiplies' (<em>marbeh</em>) the unfaithful — infidelity spreads like a contagion through her influence.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The famous wine-warning (23:29-35) opens with a cascade of rhetorical questions listing wine's social consequences. 'Grief, anguish, quarreling, needless wounds, bleary eyes' — each describes a recognizable symptom. The literary structure itself mimics the disorientation of intoxication: rapid questions, accumulating images, no single coherent answer.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'Those who linger over wine and go looking for spiced wine' (<em>haba lachqor mimsakh</em>) — the habitual seeking of mixed wine, which was wine enhanced with spices and herbs to increase potency. Ancient wine was often diluted with water; mixing in spices increased the intoxicating effect. The one who 'lingers' (<em>acharim</em>) is not an occasional drinker but one who extends drinking sessions past their natural end.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'Do not look at wine when it is red and sparkling in the cup, when it goes down smoothly' — the temptation is visual and gustatory before it is experiential. The warning targets the seductive appearance of wine at the moment of offer — the appeal is to present pleasure, and wisdom's intervention must come before the first look.</p>",
    "32": "<p>'In the end it bites like a snake and stings like a viper' (<em>nachash yishakh vesaruf yefarsesh</em>) — the delayed consequence of present pleasure. The snake-metaphor for wine's delayed harm is vivid: wine's initial smoothness (31) gives way to venom's bite. Snake imagery for hidden danger is widely attested in ANE literature; here it is deployed with unusual psychological precision — the bite comes after the swallowing.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'Your eyes will see things that are not there, and your heart will say perverse things' — hallucination and moral disorder as the twin effects of intoxication. The visual distortion (seeing what is not there) and the cognitive distortion (perverse speech) together describe the dissolution of the reliable self that sober wisdom requires. Intoxication is an epistemic problem as much as a moral one.</p>",
    "34": "<p>'You will be like one asleep in the middle of the sea, like one sprawled on top of a ship's mast' — nautical imagery for extreme disorientation. Both images describe positions of maximum danger combined with maximum insensibility: asleep in a sea storm, draped across a swaying mast. The ancient Mediterranean sailor's situation was proverbially dangerous; the drunkard is equally imperiled but equally unaware.</p>",
    "35": "<p>'They beat me, but I felt no pain' — the analgesia of intoxication followed by the addict's refrain: 'When will I wake up so I can have another drink?' The cycle of blackout and craving is described with clinical accuracy. This is not a moral caricature but an observed behavioral loop; the wisdom tradition is naming addiction before the concept existed.</p>"
  },
  "24": {
    "1": "<p>'Do not envy evil people' — the temptation of the young to admire the apparent freedom and success of those who disregard wisdom's constraints. In the ANE patronage world, the wicked could achieve visible prosperity through corruption; the wisdom tradition had to address the psychological pull of that success directly.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Their heart plans violence' — the interior reality behind the evil person's apparent success. The wise person sees through the surface prosperity to the destructive orientation beneath. Heart (<em>lev</em>) and lips (<em>sefataim</em>) as the interior and exterior of the evil person — both corrupted.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'By wisdom a house is built, and by understanding it is established' — the building metaphor for wisdom's constructive social role. A 'house' in the ANE was not merely a physical structure but a dynastic unit: the house of David, the house of such-and-such. Wisdom-building is the building of lasting social structures and family lines.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Through knowledge the rooms are filled with precious and pleasant treasures' — the interior filling that follows the structural establishment. The progression (build, establish, fill) mirrors the creation narrative of Gen 1 (form, then fill). Wisdom is cosmogonic in its operation: it brings order and abundance.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'A wise man is strong' (<em>chacham be'oz</em>) — wisdom as a form of power. In ANE court culture, the sage's power was precisely intellectual: strategic counsel, knowledge of precedent, ability to read situations. The emphasis on wisdom-as-strength counters the assumption that physical or military force was the only meaningful power.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'By wise guidance you can wage war' (<em>betachbulot taasseh lekha milchamah</em>) — <em>tachbulot</em> (wise guidance, steering) is a nautical metaphor: the pilot's skill in maneuvering a ship. Applied to warfare, it describes strategic rather than merely tactical intelligence. 'Victory depends on having many advisers' — ANE kings maintained councils of wise men for precisely this reason.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Wisdom is beyond a fool's reach; he has nothing to say at the city gate' — the gate as the venue for public deliberation. The fool's inability to contribute at the gate (the civic and legal assembly) marks his social disqualification. Wisdom was not merely private virtue but the qualification for public participation in ANE city life.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Whoever schemes to do evil will be known as a troublemaker' (<em>ba'al mezimmot</em>) — the one who devises evil plans. The social exposure of the schemer — 'will be known' — reflects the tight-knit community in which reputation was impossible to fully conceal over time. Evil schemes eventually identify their authors.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'The intention behind foolish schemes is sin' — the moral evaluation reaches inside the planning stage. ANE legal codes generally focused on action; Proverbs' wisdom tradition extends the moral assessment backward to intention, a development that anticipates the NT's heart-ethics.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'If you falter in times of trouble, how small is your strength' (<em>im hitrafita beyom tsarah tsar kochekha</em>) — the test of character reveals its depth. 'Trouble' (<em>tsarah</em>) is the Proverbs and Psalms word for the affliction that tests — the genuine crisis in which wisdom's reservoir is either drawn on or found empty. Performance under pressure reveals genuine versus nominal formation.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Rescue those being taken away to death; hold back those stumbling toward slaughter' — an active obligation to intervene on behalf of those facing unjust execution. In ancient judicial systems, capital sentences could be carried out swiftly and sometimes unjustly; the bystander obligation to intervene was a wisdom-tradition mandate, not merely a personal option.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Does not he who weighs the heart perceive it?' — the divine heart-reader as the answer to the 'I did not know' defense. In ANE contexts, ignorance was often a legal defense. Proverbs responds: the one who knows hearts (<em>tochen libot</em>, the 'weigher of hearts') — a divine attribute — renders that defense inadequate before God even if it succeeds before human courts.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'My son, eat honey because it is good' — honey as an analogy for wisdom. Honey was the most prized sweet in ancient Israel before cane sugar; finding a honeycomb was a significant discovery (1 Sam 14:25-29; Ps 19:10). Its natural sweetness made it the obvious sensory analogy for the pleasure of wisdom's discovery.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'So is wisdom to your soul; when you find it, there is a future' (<em>acharit vetiqvatekha lo tikaret</em>) — the same future-hope formula as 23:18. The pairing of honey-pleasure with future-hope addresses both the immediate and long-term dimensions of wisdom: it is pleasant now and secures the future. The two-dimensional appeal was the standard ANE wisdom incentive structure.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Do not lie in wait against the home of the righteous' — warning to the wicked against targeting the righteous person's household. The household (<em>naveh</em>, abode, pasture) as the unit of social security; attacking it is an attack on the righteous person's entire social existence. The specific prohibition addresses predatory wealth-transfer through legal manipulation or violence.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'A righteous person falls seven times and gets up again, but the wicked are brought down by calamity' — one of Proverbs' most memorable characterizations of moral resilience. 'Seven times' (<em>sheva yipol</em>) is the number of completeness — every conceivable fall. The righteous person's defining characteristic is not imperviousness to setback but recovery capacity. The wicked's single calamity finishes them; the righteous survive multiple ones.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Do not gloat when your enemy falls' — the prohibition of <em>schadenfreude</em>. In the ANE honor-shame system, the public downfall of an enemy was a social victory to be celebrated. Proverbs counters this: the wise person's response to an enemy's defeat is moral restraint, not public celebration. The reason given is theological: God's response to human gloating affects his justice-calculation.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Lest the LORD see it and be displeased, and he turns his anger away from your enemy' — the theological mechanism: God's displeasure at gloating may lead him to stop punishing the enemy. The proverb teaches that vindictive satisfaction at an enemy's suffering can actually undermine the justice one wanted — a sophisticated counter to the revenge impulse.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Do not fret because of evildoers or be envious of the wicked' — reprising the counsel of 24:1, now as a double prohibition: do not agitate or envy. The ANE wisdom tradition repeatedly addresses the psychological distress caused by observed injustice — the temptation either to worry about systemic unfairness or to envy those who exploit it.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'The evil person has no future reward; the lamp of the wicked will be snuffed out' — the lamp (<em>ner</em>) as the image of life and household vitality (cf. 13:9, 20:20). In ancient homes, the household lamp was kept burning through the night as a sign of life; its extinction was a potent symbol of death and dynastic extinction.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Fear the LORD and the king, and do not associate with those who seek to undermine either' — the double loyalty of the wise person: to divine and human authority. ANE court wisdom consistently taught loyalty to the ruling power as a practical and moral obligation. The parallel structure places fear of the LORD and fear of the king in the same category — not equating them but recognizing both as legitimate authority structures.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Their disaster will come suddenly, and who knows what destruction may come from both?' — the unpredictability of both divine and royal punishment for those who undermine authority. The wise person does not need to calculate timing; the certainty of eventual disaster is sufficient motivation for loyalty.</p>",
    "23": "<p>24:23-34 forms a small appendix: 'these also are sayings of the wise' (<em>gam elleh lachachamim</em>) — indicating a secondary collection. The opening concern is judicial impartiality, the foundational legal principle of the Mosaic law (Deut 16:19; Lev 19:15). Partiality in judgment corrupts the entire system on which community order depends.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'Whoever tells the guilty, You are innocent, will be cursed by peoples and condemned by nations' — the international scope of the condemnation is striking: nations curse the corrupt judge. In the ANE context where Israel interacted with surrounding peoples, legal reputation was not merely a domestic matter. Judicial corruption undermined the entire society's claim to moral order.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'Those who rebuke the wicked will find delight' — the positive reward for judicial courage. Rebuking the wicked in a court context was socially risky; the wise person who did so anyway received both personal satisfaction (<em>naim</em>, delight) and divine blessing (<em>birkat tov</em>, a good blessing).</p>",
    "26": "<p>'Whoever gives an honest answer is like a kiss on the lips' — the intimacy and pleasure of truthful speech. The kiss (<em>nashaq</em>) in the ANE context was both a greeting between intimates and a gesture of covenant-making. An honest answer in a difficult situation is as welcome and as relationship-building as a kiss.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'Prepare your outdoor work and get your fields ready; after that, build your house' — the sequence of priorities: productive capacity before domestic comfort. In an agricultural economy, the field is the income-generator; the house is consumption. Establishing the productive base before building the household reflects the wisdom that sustainable prosperity requires productive infrastructure.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'Do not testify against your neighbor without cause' — the legal protection against false witness. The Mosaic law's ninth commandment (Exod 20:16) is here given its practical wisdom form. In ancient communities without formal investigation procedures, false witness was easy and devastating; the prohibition had to be reiterated in multiple forms.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'Do not say, I will do to him what he did to me; I will repay him' — the retaliatory impulse addressed directly. The wisdom tradition counters both private vengeance (leave it to God and the courts) and the anticipatory planning of retribution ('do not say'). The planning stage of revenge is the point at which wisdom must intervene.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The sluggard's field (24:30-34) is a wisdom poem using observed experience as the basis for instruction. 'I passed by the field of a lazy man' — the first-person observation is the wisdom teacher's method: he walks through the world with eyes open and draws lessons from what he sees. The field is a specific, visible object lesson.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'All overgrown with thorns; the ground covered with nettles; the stone wall in ruins' — the three-fold description of agricultural abandonment. Each element represents a specific failure of maintenance: cleared ground (to thorns), tilled ground (to nettles), built structures (to ruin). The comprehensive neglect is the visible result of the invisible character flaw.</p>",
    "32": "<p>'I saw it and took it to heart; I looked and received instruction' (<em>vaetbonena lakachti musar</em>) — the wisdom method: attentive observation becomes moral formation. <em>Musar</em> (instruction, discipline) is received not from a teacher but from a ruined field. Creation itself is a teacher for the one with eyes to see.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'A little sleep, a little slumber, a little folding of the hands to rest' — the incremental nature of sloth. Each step is small and individually justifiable; the cumulative effect is catastrophic. The repetition of 'a little' (<em>meat</em>) three times mimics the self-deceptive reasoning of the sluggard who never makes a decisive choice for inaction but drifts there through small compromises.</p>",
    "34": "<p>'Then poverty will come on you like a wanderer, and your need like an armed man' — the suddenness and violence of poverty's arrival. The wanderer (<em>mehalekh</em>) appears without warning; the armed man (<em>ish magen</em>) cannot be resisted. The proverb's conclusion matches Prov 6:9-11; the same observation closes both the earlier and later collections — its repetition signals its importance as a foundational wisdom axiom.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'proverbs')
    merge_comm(existing, PROVERBS)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'proverbs', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in PROVERBS.values())
    print(f'proverbs mkt-context: wrote {total} verses across ch 22-24')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
